# Renderer Process Development Rules

## MANDATORY COMPONENT PATTERNS

### Component Type Definition
- ALWAYS use explicit props interface + explicit return type
- NEVER use React.FC or implicit typing
- REQUIRED format: `(props: PropsInterface): React.JSX.Element`

```typescript
// CORRECT
interface ButtonProps {
  text: string;
  onClick: () => void;
}

const Button = ({ text, onClick }: ButtonProps): React.JSX.Element => {
  return <button onClick={onClick}>{text}</button>;
};

// INCORRECT
const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({ text, onClick }) => {
  return <button onClick={onClick}>{text}</button>;
};
```

## STATE MANAGEMENT HIERARCHY

### 1. Local Component State
- Use `useState` for simple state
- Use `useReducer` for complex state logic
- Keep state as close to usage as possible

### 2. Feature-Scope State
- Use React Context for shared state within feature modules
- Avoid prop drilling beyond 2 levels

### 3. Global App State
- Use Zustand with slice-based architecture
- Implement atomic selectors with `useShallow`
- Use middleware stack: `devtools(persist(subscribeWithSelector(immer())))`

### 4. Main Process Integration
- Use IPC for main process communication
- Treat main process data as async source
- Implement proper loading/error states

## FORBIDDEN PATTERNS

- ❌ `React.FC` usage
- ❌ Browser localStorage (team policy)
- ❌ Manual `memo`/`useMemo` without profiling
- ❌ Class components
- ❌ CommonJS require/module.exports

## REQUIRED PATTERNS

- ✅ Functional components with hooks
- ✅ Explicit TypeScript typing
- ✅ Immutable state updates
- ✅ Pure render functions
- ✅ Error boundaries for error handling
- ✅ Loading states for async operations
- ✅ Kebab-case file naming

## FILE ORGANIZATION RULES

- Components: `src/renderer/src/components/`
- Hooks: `src/renderer/src/hooks/`
- Utilities: `src/renderer/src/lib/`
- Styles: `src/renderer/src/styles/`

## ACCESSIBILITY PRIORITY

- Phase 1: Core functionality implementation
- Phase 2: Accessibility features (later iterations)
- Focus on development efficiency first

  - Pure reducers separated from actions for testability
  - Atomic selectors with `useShallow` for object selections
  - Conditional persistence (only necessary state)
